V-P-C peering.

V-P-C Peering is a direct, point-to-point connection between two V-P-Cs that lets instances in each reach the other by private I-P, as if they were on the same network. It works same account or cross-account, same region or cross-region, using AWS's backbone with no bandwidth cap.

The constraints are sharper than people expect. C-I-D-R blocks cannot overlap: if both V-P-Cs use ten-dot-zero-dot-zero-dot-zero-slash-sixteen, peering simply won't establish. Peering is non-transitive: if A peers with B, and B peers with C, traffic from A still cannot reach C through B; you need a direct A-to-C peering. And after accepting the request, you have to update the route tables on both sides to point at the peering connection, or the connection exists but no traffic flows.

One nice property: within the same region, a security group rule can reference a security group in the peered V-P-C. "Allow port five-four-three-two from the app-tier security group in the other V-P-C" works directly. Peering is the right tool for two to a few V-P-Cs. Past a handful, the full mesh, which needs N-times-N-minus-one-over-two connections, collapses, and you move to Transit Gateway.
